<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pionex Earn &amp; Savings Review</span></h2>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Savings</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pionex doesn’t use the word “savings” like your regular bank. Instead, you’ll find things like the “Earn / Flexible Product” and the Arbitrage product under the “Earn” tab. These let you put in your crypto and earn a yield that is kind of similar to savings, but the returns come from crypto market strategies, not just a fixed interest rate.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;"><img decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-194959" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Pionex-savings.jpg" alt="Pionex savings" width="1363" height="631" /></span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Flexible Product is a big one. You can deposit or take out your funds whenever you want, no lock-up periods, and you start earning rewards every hour.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Then there’s the Arbitrage product, which stands out too. Here, Pionex lets you invest in arbitrage strategies, combining spot and perpetual futures markets to collect returns from funding rates.</span></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Lending</span></h3>
<p><a href="https://www.pionex.com/blog/zh-bitfinex-introduce-en/" data-wpel-link="external" rel="external noopener noreferrer"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pionex Lending</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> lets you earn interest by lending out certain cryptocurrencies on Pionex. It’s not a direct peer-to-peer setup, though. Instead, Pionex connects to the Bitfinex lending market behind the scenes. They use their own algorithms to lend your funds on Bitfinex and then pass the interest back to you.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">You can pick fixed terms, like 14 or 30 days, so your crypto isn’t tied up forever. The interest rates change depending on what’s happening on Bitfinex’s market, Pionex doesn’t promise a set return. Sometimes, they’ll pause the lending service for maintenance or other reasons. During these times, you might not be able to subscribe or redeem, but your funds can still earn interest. Over time, Pionex has changed which assets you can lend, too. For example, they stopped supporting USDC at one point.</span></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Mining</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">On Pionex, the closest thing to “mining” is running trading bots, especially the Grid Trading Bot, to take advantage of price swings. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Here’s how it works: the bot sets up a bunch of limit buy and sell orders in a price range, snapping up coins when prices dip and selling them off when they climb. It’s like picking up small profits over and over. But let’s be clear, this isn’t real mining. There’s no block validation, no new coins popping into existence. Everything you earn comes straight from trading.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pionex gives you plenty of ways to tweak your setup. You can set your own price range, decide how many grids you want, use take profit and stop-loss tools, control slippage, and even choose between arithmetic or geometric grids.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">There’s a reverse grid bot, too. With this one, you measure your profit in the base currency like ETH instead of the quote currency, say USDT. It’s a handy way to stack up more of the coin you want. And if you really want to dive deep, there’s the Coin-M Futures Grid Bot with a Hedging Strategy. This lets you run a 1x short position alongside your grid, so you can make money off both price swings and funding rates, without worrying about getting liquidated.</span></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Loans</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pionex provides a couple of loan-related products:</span></p>
<ul>
<li aria-level="1"><b>Margin Grid Bot (Borrowing / Collateral)</b></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">With Pionex Margin Grid, you put up one crypto as collateral and borrow another to kick off your grid trading strategy. Leverage isn’t unlimited, you get anywhere from 1x to 5x. You’ll pay interest on whatever you borrow. The daily rate isn’t fixed; it shifts every 8 hours, depending on demand. If your grid bot keeps running, Pionex just takes the interest straight from your bot’s unrealized or grid profits. One thing to watch out for is liquidation risk. Before you start, Pionex shows you an estimated liquidation price. If the market hits that number, your collateral gets liquidated.</span><b></b></p>
<ul>
<li aria-level="1"><b>Structured Loans</b></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This works like a regular loan. You put up a crypto asset, like BTC, as collateral and borrow USDT against it. Pionex says you can borrow quite a bit, sometimes 60% to 80% of what your collateral’s worth. They add a twist too, you agree on a profit-sharing level and ratio when you borrow, so both sides share in any gains. Plus, there’s a safety net. If your collateral’s price drops below a certain level by the end of the loan, Pionex steps in with some compensation.</span></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Dual Asset Investment</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">With </span><a href="https://www.pionex.com/blog/dual-investment/" data-wpel-link="external" rel="external noopener noreferrer"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Dual Investment</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, you get to pick the price and date you want to buy at. Plus, you can earn a pretty high interest on your asset. Just keep in mind, Dual Investment isn’t principal-protected, it’s a structured product, so there’s some risk involved. When you make a purchase, you choose the asset, the currency you want to invest in, the amount, and when you want it delivered. Your return comes in either your chosen currency or an alternate one, depending on certain conditions:</span></p>
<ul>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">If settlement price ≥ target, you receive your return in the investment currency (e.g USDT) </span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">If settlement price &lt; target, you receive in the target currency (e.g BTC) based on the target price. </span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">You won’t pay any transaction fees when you buy Dual Investment products. Once you place an order, you can’t cancel it. But if you want out before settlement, you’ve got the Early Redemption option.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pionex has an auto-invest mode too. You just set up a bot with your target price or preferred APR, and it keeps subscribing to Dual Investment products for you.</span></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pionex Card</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The </span><a href="https://support.pionex.com/hc/en-us/articles/48789380813977-Pionex-Card-Feature-Overview" data-wpel-link="external" rel="external noopener noreferrer"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pionex Card</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> isn’t a credit card rather, it’s a crypto debit card. You’ll need to load money onto it before you can use it. Right now, it only lets you spend USDT. The card is virtual, so there’s no physical version at the moment.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">You can use it with any merchant that takes Visa, whether you’re shopping online or paying in-store with a linked wallet. Just remember, you have to move your funds from your main Pionex account into your card account before you spend anything.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pionex Launchpad Review</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">While the platform stands out for its built-in trading bots, but it doesn’t actually run a typical launchpad for ICOs or new token sales like Binance or KuCoin. </span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pionex NFT Marketplace Review</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">While the platform is best known as a crypto exchange with built-in, free automated trading bots. That’s really its main thing, helping people trade spot and futures with smart tools. You can trade more than 320 different cryptocurrencies there, including a few tokens tied to the NFT world. For example, they supported the APENFT airdrop for TRX holders. But if you’re looking to buy, sell, or mint individual NFTs, you’re out of luck. Pionex doesn’t run an NFT marketplace at all.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pionex Referral And Affiliate Programs Review</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">With the </span><a href="https://www.pionex.com/blog/pionex-affiliate-program-2/" data-wpel-link="external" rel="external noopener noreferrer"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pionex Referral Program</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, you can invite friends to join Pionex and earn bonuses whenever they trade. Hit a certain trading volume, and you’re just a click away from joining the Pionex Partner or </span><a href="https://www.pionex.com/blog/pionex-affiliate-program-2/" data-wpel-link="external" rel="external noopener noreferrer"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pionex Affiliate Program</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">. Here, you get access to rebates starting at 20% for Spot trading and 15% for Futures. The more you and your referrals trade, the more you can earn. There’s really no cap on your potential.</span></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Commission Structure</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">When you invite friends to trade spot (including leveraged tokens), you get 20% of their trading fees as commission. For futures trading, the commission is 15%. You can actually share some of your commission with your friends, giving them a discount on their trading fees. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Beyond the base rates, there are performance tiers. If your referrals trade a lot, or you bring in a bunch of new users who actually register and deposit at least 100 USDT, your commission rate can go up. For example, if you hit “Agent” level, you earn up to 50% on spot trades and 40% on futures.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The platform checks your commission tier every month (on the 1st, UTC), looking at how many valid users you’ve brought in and how much they’re trading.</span></p>
<h2 data-pm-slice="1 1 []"><span data-color="var(--green-10)">Pionex Security Review: Compliance with Federal and State Laws</span></h2>
<p>People usually see Pionex as a legit platform, but it&#8217;s not without risks. They use standard security practices, and they went through a security incident before plus, some users have complained. Pionex holds a U.S. Money Services Business license from FinCEN, and they get audited on a regular basis.</p>
<h3>Reserve Transparency and Proof of Solvency</h3>
<p>Pionex really leans on its 100% Proof of Reserves as a major trust signal. They use a Merkle Tree system, so every user can check their own balance against the exchange&#8217;s records without seeing anyone else&#8217;s info. On top of that, two outside firms Elite Partners and Moore audited the numbers. They confirmed that, at the time of their review, Pionex actually held more in reserves for big assets like BTC, ETH, and stablecoins than it owed to users.</p>
<h3>Account Security Measures</h3>
<p>Pionex pushes users to keep their accounts secure:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Two-factor Authentication (2FA)</strong>: First, they really want you to turn on two-factor authentication; something like Google Authenticator works well, allowing you to <span data-color="var(--green-10)">scan QR code </span>during the setup process.</li>
<li><strong>KYC Verification</strong>: They also ask you to complete KYC verification. This not only increases your withdrawal limits but also makes your account more trustworthy in their eyes, so it&#8217;s safer.</li>
<li><strong>Phishing Protection</strong>: And don&#8217;t forget about phishing. Pionex keeps reminding users to double-check the website address to make sure you&#8217;re actually on <a href="http://pionex.com/" target="_blank" rel="external noopener noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external">pionex.com</a> and to steer clear of sketchy links in emails.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Infrastructure and Custody Security</h3>
<p>Pionex says they keep about 95% of user funds in cold wallets (offline storage), that&#8217;s much harder for hackers to reach. They use SSL encryption too, so your data and login details stay protected while moving across the internet. Moreover, Pionex has a variety of other measures: firewalls, additional encryption, and strict access protocols are all factors keeping user data secure.</p>
<h2>Pionex Mobile App Review</h2>
<h3 data-path-to-node="2"><b data-path-to-node="2" data-index-in-node="0">User Interface &amp; Performance</b></h3>
<p data-path-to-node="3">Pionex is praised by <i data-path-to-node="3" data-index-in-node="21">DayTrading.com</i> for its clean, beginner-friendly design that makes switching between spot, futures, and bots seamless. However, users on G2 and Reddit frequently report <b data-path-to-node="3" data-index-in-node="189">UI freezes and lag</b>, especially when opening positions or loading charts. There are also known <b data-path-to-node="3" data-index-in-node="283">syncing issues</b> where transaction history doesn&#8217;t always match between the mobile app and the web version.</p>
<h3 data-path-to-node="4"><b data-path-to-node="4" data-index-in-node="0">Trading Bots &amp; Customization</b></h3>
<p data-path-to-node="5">The platform’s main draw is its built-in bots (Grid, DCA, Arbitrage) and copy-trading. A key limitation is that <b data-path-to-node="5" data-index-in-node="112">copy-trading must be set up via the mobile app</b>, as the web version (Edge, Firefox, etc.) does not support it. Additionally, advanced traders may find the platform restrictive since it <b data-path-to-node="5" data-index-in-node="296">does not allow</b> for custom strategies or external indicators.</p>
<h3 data-path-to-node="6"><b data-path-to-node="6" data-index-in-node="0">Security &amp; Regulatory Concerns</b></h3>
<p data-path-to-node="7">Pionex uses 2FA, Google Authenticator, and cold storage to protect funds, alongside mandatory KYC and regular audits. However, a <b data-path-to-node="7" data-index-in-node="129">2026 consent order</b> highlighted past compliance failures regarding fund transfers. While the app is functional, these regulatory issues suggest users should weigh the platform&#8217;s features against its legal track record.</p>
<h2>Pionex Customer Support Review</h2>
