					<description><![CDATA[<p>Nearfield Instruments, a leader in cutting-edge semiconductor 3D metrology and process control, announced a hugely oversubscribed $380M series D funding round. The large round officially values the Rotterdam-headquartered company at</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/nearfield-instruments-raises-380m-to-boost-ai-chipmaking/" data-wpel-link="internal">Nearfield Instruments Raises $380M to Boost AI Chipmaking</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.nearfieldinstruments.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Nearfield Instruments</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">, a leader in cutting-edge semiconductor 3D metrology and process control, announced a hugely oversubscribed $380M series D </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/odyssey-raises-310m-shifts-focus-to-amazon-and-imd/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">funding </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">round. The large round officially values the Rotterdam-headquartered company at $1.6 billion, making it the largest deep tech funding round ever in the Netherlands.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Fidelity Management and Research Company led the round with contributions from Temasek (Singapore), Walden Catalyst Ventures, Innovation Industries, M&amp; G Investments, and Invest.nl. Qatar Investment Authority (QIA) also came in as a key new investor for the oversubscribed round, while existing backers TNO Ventures and ING also increased their investment.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Solving the Infrastructure Bottleneck of the AI Boom</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The massive injection of capital arrives at a critical juncture for the global technology ecosystem. As artificial intelligence models expand exponentially in capability and size, they require vastly more powerful silicon processors to handle data. However, chipmakers are running into severe structural engineering limitations. Fabricating the microscopic transistors necessary for next-generation AI hardware requires working at a molecular scale where even the slightest atomic variation can ruin a batch of silicon.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_203007" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-203007" class="size-large wp-image-203007" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/AI-chip-1-1024x576.jpg" alt="AI chip" width="1024" height="576" /><p id="caption-attachment-203007" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Unsplash</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">To maximize computing power while keeping energy consumption manageable, the semiconductor industry is moving away from traditional, flat chip designs. Manufacturers are pivoting toward highly complex three-dimensional architectures. While these 3D designs allow more processing power to be crammed into a tight space, verifying that these vertical structures are being manufactured correctly has become a primary bottleneck for global chip foundries.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/odyssey-raises-310m-shifts-focus-to-amazon-and-imd/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Odyssey Raises $310M, Shifts Focus to Amazon and IMD</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Measuring Features Only a Few Atoms Tall</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This is where Nearfield Instruments provides a vital solution through its specialization in advanced semiconductor metrology, which is the intricate science of measuring and inspecting the microscopic features etched onto silicon wafers. Traditional optical measurement techniques are failing because they cannot look deep inside vertical channels or measure hidden sidewalls without destroying the chip.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Nearfield Instruments addresses this through its proprietary high-throughput atomic force microscopy technology, most notably deployed in its QUADRA platform. The machine acts similarly to an ultra-precise record player needle. It gently drags an atomic-scale probe across the surface of a wafer to map out three-dimensional features that are only a few atoms tall.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Crucially, the platform performs these non-destructive 3D measurements in-line during high-volume manufacturing. Foundries can catch physical defects in real-time across hundreds of sequential production phases rather than waiting until the end of a long manufacturing cycle.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Enabling Next-Generation Chip Architectures</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The technical capabilities of the technology are aimed at supporting advanced fabrication processes. This includes Gate-All-Around and complementary field-effect transistor architectures, which are the highly complex transistor patterns driving future high-performance computing chips. The imaging technology is also optimized to measure multi-layered stacks, high-aspect-ratio trenches, and the microscopic connections required for hybrid-bonded 3D integrated circuits.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">By providing atomic-level visibility into these complex structures, Nearfield Instruments helps major chip foundries optimize their production yields. Higher yield rates directly lower manufacturing costs and accelerate the commercial rollout of the highly efficient hardware needed to sustain global AI infrastructure.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/nearfield-instruments-raises-380m-to-boost-ai-chipmaking/" data-wpel-link="internal">Nearfield Instruments Raises $380M to Boost AI Chipmaking</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
